          "body": "The chapter's two-part structure (vv. 1-6 under Moses; vv. 7-24 under Joshua) makes a quiet but significant theological point: the conquest of the promised land required two generations and two leaders working in sequence, and neither generation's work was complete without the other. Moses defeated Sihon and Og east of the Jordan (Numbers 21) and gave that territory to Reuben, Gad, and half-Manasseh (v. 6). Joshua defeated thirty-one kings west of the Jordan and gave the land to all the tribes (v. 7). The chapter holds them together in a single document, giving equal formal weight to both. Moses is called 'the servant of the LORD' twice in verse 6 — a title that in the Deuteronomistic history is almost exclusively Moses' (cf. Deuteronomy 34:5; Joshua 1:1). His victories are not diminished because he did not cross the Jordan; they are essential to everything Joshua accomplished. The plan of God spans human generations without being dependent on any single one."
