          "body": "Beginning at verse 9, the chapter shifts from prose description to liturgical enumeration. The formula is stark and unvarying: 'the king of ___, one.' Sixteen verses, thirty-one iterations. The reader who has followed the narrative through chapters 6-11 knows the stories behind many of these names — Jericho's walls, the ambush at Ai, the coalition at the waters of Merom, the burning of Hazor. Here they are reduced to a single syllable. The rhetorical effect is deliberate and cumulative. Each 'one' is a closed account. Each 'one' is a sovereignty that marshaled armies, erected fortifications, and consolidated regional power — and is now numbered among the defeated. Spurgeon, preaching on similar Old Testament victory lists, noted that the glory belongs entirely to the One who is not named in the list: 'The enemies are counted; God is not — because you do not count what is infinite.' The chapter is a doxology written in names and numbers."
