        "excerpt": "Moses the servant of the LORD and the sons of Israel defeated them; and Moses the servant of the LORD gave it to the Reubenites and the Gadites and the half-tribe of Manasseh as a possession.",
        "body": "Verses 1-6 function as a formal legal certification of territory already described in Numbers 21 and Deuteronomy 2-3. Sihon's kingdom ran from Aroer on the Arnon's rim to the Jabbok River — roughly seventy miles of the Transjordanian plateau. Og's kingdom extended from the Jabbok northward to Mount Hermon, encompassing all of Bashan. Together, these two kings controlled the entire eastern approach to Canaan, and both had already refused Israel's peaceful passage (Numbers 21:21-35; Deuteronomy 2:26-3:7). Their defeat was not incidental; it was the prerequisite for the western campaign.\n\nThe chapter's identification of Og as 'one of the remnant of the Rephaim' (v. 4) is exegetically significant. The Rephaim were the indigenous giant-clans of Canaan and Transjordan (Genesis 14:5; 15:20; Deuteronomy 2:11, 20; 3:11). Their presence was the primary psychological obstacle that defeated the first generation — Numbers 13:33 records the spies' report that 'we were like grasshoppers in our own sight' before these men. Deuteronomy 3:11 preserves the memory of Og's bed as a public monument. By noting that Og was 'one of the remnant,' the author signals that even the most fearsome category of opponent was not only defeatable but already being extinguished. The Anakim of Cisjordan will be addressed in Joshua 11:21-22; the conquest of Og completes the same theological point east of the Jordan.\n\nVerse 6 closes the section with the double title 'Moses the servant of the LORD' — appearing twice in a single verse. In the Deuteronomistic history, this title is Moses' signature designation (cf. Deuteronomy 34:5; Joshua 1:1, 2, 7, 13, 15; 2 Kings 18:12). Its repetition here is not redundancy but emphasis: the agent of these victories is identified not by his military rank but by his relationship to the LORD. The victories belong to the LORD because they were won through His servant. This is the Old Testament's consistent pattern: the leader is magnified by his servant-relation to God, not despite it.\n\nThe distribution to Reuben, Gad, and half-Manasseh (v. 6) completes a legal circuit: God fought through Moses, Moses distributed through divine mandate (Numbers 32; Deuteronomy 3:12-20). The land was never Israel's by right of arms; it was Israel's by gift of covenant. The conquest is simultaneously military and sacramental.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Eved YHWH* (servant of the LORD) — the *eved* relationship in the ancient Near East was a formal covenant-bond of loyalty and delegated authority. Moses' victories are performed *as* the LORD's agent, not independently. *Yerushshah* (possession, inheritance) — from the same root as *yarash* (to possess, dispossess, v. 1), carrying both the act of taking and the legal right of holding. The land is not merely seized; it is received."
